HEALING WITH THE CHAKRAS⁣
⁣
What do you do when you’re faced with an imbalance? This could be a physical imbalance such as an illness, an emotional imbalance such as fear, or a cognitive imbalance such as self-doubt.⁣
⁣
If you’re like most people, you likely either ignore it until it becomes big enough and then use external resources to treat it. You may take medicine, do some journaling, vent to a friend, etc. If you’re used to doing the inner work, then you likely have a few practices up your sleeve that you use to process and release it.⁣
⁣
But, do you deal with the energetic component of that imbalance, too?⁣
⁣
We’re so used to dealing with imbalances in external ways that we totally forget that they have an energetic root, too.⁣
⁣
The chakra system is a powerful way of navigating and healing our bodies (physical, emotional, mental bodies, etc.), which has not only been studied spiritually but scientifically, too.⁣
⁣
In my Psychic Clearing sessions, I always start by scanning people’s chakras, as it’s the fastest way to identify imbalances.⁣
⁣
During my sessions, I guide the client towards healing the energetic component of these imbalances, which escalates physical healing, too.⁣
⁣
In this week’s episode of The Lit Up Lightworker Podcast, bestselling author of Trust Your Truth @shannon.algeo, shares a framework for healing and doing the inner work through the chakra system.⁣
⁣
Specifically, in this episode you’ll learn:⁣
⁣
✦ How to overcome self-doubt and boost your self-esteem⁣
✦ A practice to heal codependency and nurture healthy relationships⁣
✦ Simple ways of finding your soul’s purpose⁣
✦ How to align with your authentic self on a daily basis⁣
✦ A process of getting to the root cause of your limiting beliefs⁣
⁣
Watch the full interview on YouTube, or listen to it on Spotify and Apple Podcasts.⁣
⁣

Therapy is a privilege, but is also a necessity. And it should be a right. “The right to therapy” has a ring to it, am I rite?

I firmly believe with my whole heart that any and EVERY person willing to do the brave work of looking inward to heal old patterns of trauma should be provided with high quality mental health care services.

Therapy has changed my life and continues to unlock the spaces within me where I am constricted so I can get a little more free. We all deserve the opportunity to be witnessed, seen, validated, mirrored, encouraged, and held.

For the last year and half, I have been volunteering at a community mental health center as a pre-licensed therapist. If you or someone you know is looking for a psychotherapist but are feeling burdened by cost, consider looking for a community mental health center or clinic in your community that provides sliding scales services.

For me, therapy is as necessary as my groceries. It’s non-negotiable. This life we live is wild and some days on this earth can be gnarly. I hope we all can get access to the support we need and so deserve.

Feel free to leave any valuable mental heath resources in the comments 👇🏼

Thank you @yourdiagnonsense for this quote and image.

Yesterday, I received final approval on my graduate school thesis!

I am feeling a big sigh of joyous relief with the completion of this research project.

It was fascinating, rewarding, insightful, and illuminating. I am humbled by what I learned—through both reporting on decades of research and having my own embodied experience. 

The thesis, titled “Soul Retrieval: Poetry Therapy for Recovery of the Lost Self from Smartphone Attachment,” will be a published contribution to the field of psychology research, and it will be available for anyone to access and read for free.

Here I am sharing this with you from my smartphone—oh the irony! But I have a feeling that will change again soon.

More to come! 🤓📚🙏🏼💚

Research conducted by marketing expert Adrian Ward et al. (2017) revealed the presence of “brain drain,” or impaired cognitive function, in college students whose smartphones were present on their desk or in their pocket when compared to students who removed their smartphone from the room. The researchers concluded “that signals from one’s own phone (but not someone else’s) activate the same involuntary attention system that responds to the sound of one’s own name,” causing a “gravitational pull” that decreases cognitive function and ability to focus.

🤳🏻 Challenge for you: 
1. Identify an important task or creative project you want to focus on (school assignment, blog post, reading a book, connecting with a friend, etc.

2. Turn your phone OFF or put it on airplane mode

3. Put it FACE DOWN in a drawer in another room.

4. If helpful, identify an amount of time you would like to me off your phone (90 minutes, 1 hour, 6 hours, more?)

5. Dive into your REAL LIFE, baby!

Let me know how it goes and what’s working well for you 💚

This is why I now avoid having important conversations via text.

Texting lacks presence, tone of voice, context, facial expression, breath, eye contact, mirroring, and all of the nuanced qualities of person-to-person relating that the human brain has used for thousands of years as the basis of knowledge and for the evolution of consciousness.

The author of Digital Minimalism Cal Newport (2019) wrote,
“The idea that real-world interactions are more valuable than online interactions isn’t surprising. Our brains evolved during a period when the only communication was offline and face-to-face. . . . These offline interactions are incredibly rich because they require our brains to process large amounts of information about subtle analog cues such as body language, facial expressions, and voice tone.”

We need more from each other. And yes, it can be scary to have conversations that require emotional risk. Do what you can, when you. Be brave and gentle with yourself as you try new things. 💜🙏🏼

#mirrorneurons #interpersonalneurobiology #weneedeachother #psychology #smartphoneaddiction #digitaldetox

Sourcing your self worth from the inside out is important, yes. But it is also perfectly healthy—and essential—to get approval, validation, love, and praise from the outside in.

We are hard wired for connection and need validation from others in order to thrive. So don’t judge yourself harshly for having needs.

Some days, self-validation may be the balm that soothes an aching sense of self. But on other days, you may need a loved one to remind you of the badass who you are.

If needing other people feels scary or unsafe, slowly allowing yourself to receive love from others can be a big and brave practice of opening your heart and rewiring your relational experience toward something new. Go slow and trust that you know best what you need.

When I first heard this poem Beannacht (Gaelic for Blessing) by the late Irish poet John O’Donohue on @onbeing, my soul was deeply stirred, and I felt compelled to memorize it, repeat it, share it, offer it.

John O’Donohue wrote this Blessing for his mother after his father passed, and it speaks to the moments where you feel ‘the weight deaden on your shoulders’ and ‘the ghost of loss gets into you.’ I find it to be incredibly nourishing, and I hope you receive this Blessing- that it provides some soul balm for any aching or grieving parts.

Here is the full text of the poem, 
BEANNACHT by John O’Donohue:

On the day when
the weight deadens
on your shoulders
and you stumble,
may the clay dance
to balance you.

And when your eyes
freeze behind
the grey window
and the ghost of loss
gets into you,
may a flock of colours,
indigo, red, green
and azure blue,
come to awaken in you
a meadow of delight.

When the canvas frays
in the currach of thought
and a stain of ocean
blackens beneath you,
may there come across the waters
a path of yellow moonlight
to bring you safely home.

May the nourishment of the earth be yours,
may the clarity of light be yours,
may the fluency of the ocean be yours,
may the protection of the ancestors be yours.

And so may a slow
wind work these words
of love around you,
an invisible cloak
to mind your life.

#instapoetry #irishblessing #spokenwordpoetry #griefandloss #mentalhealthsupport

Research by Lembke (2021) shows that, “abstaining from technology can restore brains that have been inundated with dopamine.” 

▫️Fun fact: Yes, my SIM card is currently connected to my flip phone! 

▫️ Try it out: When I was writing the proposal for Trust Your Truth (my first book), I was having an incredibly difficult time focusing. So, I would turn my phone off on Saturday night when I went to bed, and I wouldn’t turn it back on until Monday morning after I meditated. These two days and two nights of restorative time in solitude with JUST myself were incredibly transformative and opened me up to the power of stepping away from these addictive devices.

▫️ Self-inquiry: How might you benefit from boundaries time away from your device? What emotions or thoughts come up when you even think about stepping away?

The chief science officer of the American Psychological Association (APA), Mitch Prinstein, testified before Congress in February and reported that adolescents are picking up their phones over 100 times per day (some studies show up to 250 times per day) and are spending over eight (8) hours per day on their devices.

Adolescence is a key phase of brain development and teens are experiencing a biological vulnerability that can increase compulsive / addictive smartphone use.

🤔 Prinstein also reported that over HALF of teens show at least once sign of clinical dependency, such as the inability to stop use—or significant impairment that is impacting teens’ ability to carry out simple daily functions.

▫️These devices and their applications have the potential to be highly addictive to ALL of us!

▫️Start small: Choose an amount of time (1 hour, for example) and turn your phone off, put it face down in a drawer, and set a timer (on your oven?!) Choosing a tangible goal and then achieving that small step can help you tune into yourself and assess how you feel while you are off your device. How do you feel? 
What do you notice? 
Anxiety levels? 
Body sensations? 
Relief? 

Maybe journal or speak to a friend about what came up for you.

If you are a giver, or someone who feels a sense of purpose and meaning when helping others, it is quite possible that you may end up relationships where you are settling for less than you deserve.

🥖 Why settle for breadcrumbs when you deserve the four (4) course meal, baby?

👬 Attachment theory shows that our relationships with our primary caregivers as children almost inevitably get reenacted and replicated in our most intimate adult partnerships.

So if you are someone who grew up tending to the emotional needs of your parents or caregivers, and other people’s needs took precedence over your own, it is quite possible that it may feel normal or familiar for you to EXPECT less than the healthy balance that comes from a nourishing partnership.

🌯 You deserve the whole enchilada!

Remember: You can’t do someone else’s inner work for them.

📔 Ask yourself:
(1)	What about this situation feels familiar?
(2)	How is it for me to be in the role of receiver?
(3)	Is this personal capable of meeting my needs in terms of communication, authenticity, and inner work?

In the summer of 2020, I began gathering paperwork from across the globe to initiate the process of becoming an Irish citizen. My grandfather (@mikealg ‘s father) Daniel Algoe was born in Dunfanaghy in County Donegal on October 2, 1907, which makes my dad an automatic Irish citizen and my siblings and me eligible to register as citizens through the Foreign Births Registration. (The spelling got changed from Algoe to Algeo at Ellis Island.)

I feel like I got a wink from my grandfather when the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania Department of Health happened to certify and date his 'Certificate of Death' on exactly his 113th birthday: October 2, 2020. And another wink when I got a confirmation over the phone from Ireland that my passport had been approved on the 37th anniversary of the death of my maternal grandmother Elizabeth "Betts" Stewart Cramer (@plumeriablossom ’s mother), whose ancestors also came from Ireland.

Here is a photo of my Irish passport hot off the presses alongside my U.S. one, with my grandfather's original Irish birth certificate in the background.

The process of becoming an Irish citizen took about 13 months once all my paperwork was submitted, and it took another 3 months or so to get my passport. I feel grateful to have the opportunity to reclaim citizenship in the home of my ancestors and to have access to live and work in any of the 29 countries of the EU. Thank you to all of the people who helped make this happen!! There were many angels, Notary Publics, passport photographers, family members, and agents of the state who assisted me along the way.

It is a privilege to claim citizenship with such relative ease, and I have great respect and empathy for individuals and families who are searching for a safe place to belong amidst the great challenges of this world. We all deserve to be home 💚☘️

“That even in a burning world, we still get the chills.” - @joysullivanpoet. After a week of battling Covid for the first time ever, I am feeling grateful to be alive. I am humbled by how when the shit hits the fan, so few things matter. Life gets so simple.

Is there a comforter to keep me warm?
Soup on the stove?
An available dish and spoon?
A perfectly-timed check in from a loved one?
Medicine? Water? Warmth?
An episode of Ted Lasso or Prehistoric Planet to help enter another dimension?

During one of my fever sweats, I had the thought, “at the end of the day, all we have is each other. how kind and graceful can we be as we navigate this wild life?”

I also had the thought, “where is Clay Aiken right now?” and I google’d it - and he did run for Congress in 2022.

In summary, Don’t Save It All For Christmas Day. Go big, or go home. Because home is a pretty big deal too.

Love you all - stay safe out there. Let’s take care of each other 💚

My 10-day silent meditation retreat was incredibly beautiful and so very, very challenging. Ten days is a long time to go with no speaking, no eye contact, no journal, no reading, no exercise, and no meals after 12pm (except for tea and light fruit). To abstain from all of these things with a meditation schedule that spanned from 4:30am to 9pm was incredibly challenging for me. But it was also amazingly rich and fruitful. 

I had many insightful and healing epiphanies:

1- BEING WITH MY INNER CHILD. I got to be in dialogue with my inner child and hear him say things to people he’s never gotten the chance to express. I got to assure him, validate him, love him, and soothe him.

2- CREATIVE CLARITY. I got crystal clear clarity about a creative project in works- like a divinely sent roadmap of a where to move and how to proceed.

3- X-RAY VISION. I saw my patterns. Everywhere I looked, there I was. I could not run and escape into food, my smartphone, a dating app, social media, or someone else’s problems.  Every time I turned to run away, I just saw myself there in the mirror. And this helped me to see where I run away from myself, and instead, show up for Shannon more fully. 

4- BIG LOVE. I felt the presence of loved ones with me in visceral, mystical, and spiritual ways. 

5- EMOTIONAL RELEASE. I wept, often. My heart buzzed with love and grief and relief. My heart let down its walls. And it opened.

6- SOLIDARITY. Even though I did not know their names or the sounds of their voices, I came to love the men sitting alongside me. I felt them deeply, and I felt such gratitude for the solidarity present in what we were taking on together. 

And yet, with all of these very palpable and transformative aspects of my experience, I had a very complicated experience with the way the container is held, from a psychological and trauma-informed perspective. And this was part of my decision to leave on Day 8. I chose to honor my needs, as I was having anxiety and panic attacks and needed more support.

I will share more about this, as I continue to integrate my experience and collect my thoughts. In the meantime, never be afraid to put yourself first. 🤍

I wrote this poem last summer when I experienced a sudden breakup of a quick love that felt so rich and so real. I was so ready for it, and I thought it was going to last. But it dissolved as quickly as it appeared.

This poem is called SOMETHING HOLY. It cuts off at the end of the recording bc of time constraints, so I am posting the text in its entirely below.

For me, poems are rituals. They help me move from one stage or phase of life to another. They help me give words to my grief, my love, my humanity, my soul, and my heart.

I hope this might be supportive and/or helpful to you or someone you know who has dared to love, and love again. Good job to us! We stayed brave and open, against the odds. 🫶🏼

SOMETHING HOLY:
a breakup poem by Shannon Algeo

An unspeakable sense of stun—
stopped short of union

Loss swirls 
like a sea of 
something once 
yearned for.
Desire fulfilled then emptied fast.

I am alone again,
changed by the sea. 
“Help!” “SOS!” I want to cry out. 
Yet I know inward 
is the route home to my roots 
of love of self and trust and heart.

Home to me—the one I will always see.
Shannon, I’ll never give up on you, on us.
I am here for the whole damn sacred thing. 

I am grateful for the sacred salty 
tears that cascade from my cheeks—
bouncing with the buoyancy 
of a brilliant
summer rain.

Cleansing me, restoring me,
loving and ignoring my old ways of 
lock up and shut down and 
halt. 

I’ve searched forever for you and 
suddenly you’re gone,
and achingly I’m here. 

I wished for our love and it went as fast 
as it came to remind me of Eros, 
of love, of desire, of my Sacred Soul Self. 

You were younger than I trusted
but I saw the hopeful hue
of a stable you. 

Your earth felt rich, it
unearthed an eager boy
from the ditch of my dauntingly 
cavernous heart. 

I will trust our love was real 
and sweet and uniquely ours.

With a clenched pit in my stomach
I will try to breathe
and remember your words,
 “Our bricks will forever 
  be in our foundation.” 

My foundation has been rocked, 
but maybe also built. 

I will try to remember  u s 
as I ache to forget.

There was something holy I felt with you.

You did that…

Note to Self And All Who Need It

Love,
Shannon  x 🫶🏼

Sherry Turkle, psychologist and the founding director of the MIT Initiative on Technology and Self, spent decades researching the impact of technology on the development of self and relationships to others. Turkle wrote, “Always distracted, we lost the capacity for solitude. . . . We came to ask less of each other. We settled for less empathy, less attention, less care from other human beings.”

Studies reveal that if a cell phone is present at the table where two people are having lunch, the conversation is prone to cover lighter subjects, “and each party feels less invested in the other.” Turkle linked the “empathy gap,” which marks a 40% decline over 30 years in empathy among college students, to the rise of digital communication.

Turkle wrote,
“Technology is seductive when what it offers meets our human vulnerabilities. . . . We are lonely but fearful of intimacy. Digital connections . . . offer the illusion of companionship without the demands of friendship. Our networked life allows us to hide from each other, even as we are tethered to each other. We’d rather text than talk.”

🦊 What do you notice when you leave your phone at home for an hour (or more) and go out into the world?

🐸 What do you notice unfolding in your mind? 

🙊 What sensations do you notice in your body? 

🐣 What emerges in your connections with others?

She said what she said! 👏👏

Why go ‘above and beyond’ when you can go ‘below and back’ ? 😂 

In all seriousness for a moment while I have you, the shadow of people pleasing and going “above and beyond” at the expense of one’s boundaries, needs, and self care is (or can be) … this! Anger turned inward or aggression expressed outward. 

We all have our limits. Being pushed (or pushing ourselves) well past our limits has a cost. Eventually, if we do not find balance, balance will find us through compensation. 

As Carl Jung said, “Until you make the unconscious conscious, it will direct your life and you will call it fate.” The shadow self, when made conscious, can be integrated into our Self so we can be conscious participants in our own fate, growth, and evolution. 

Send some vibes, thoughts, and condolences below if you want to hear more from this Lovely Lady™️ !

I’m sure she’s got more to say!

Emotional Pain walked into my room today, and immediately grabbed ahold of me.

I tried to fling him away. “Let go of me!” I cried. “I can’t handle you. Not today.”

For a few excruciating moments, we battled, we wrestled, we seethed, until suddenly, I softened.

He said to me, “I promise to let go of you, as soon as you see and acknowledge me.”

I felt the ton of bricks weighing on my body. Underneath the chaos of battle, I felt the hurt, the pain in my body and soul.

I breathed and journaled and wept.

I said to my feisty friend, Emotional Pain, “I see you. And I’m sorry for all the times I ignored you, repressed you, invalidated you, and dismissed you.”

“Thank you,” he said to me, as we both softened and breathed a little deeper, together.

Together, we are learning, the only way out is through, and perhaps we can befriend the most unlikely of foes.

Here’s to learning to love the shadow, my friends. And what it comes to teach us. On this Friday the 13th.

Gratefully yours,
Shannon 🤍

The war between Israel and Hamas brings up many memories from my 9-day trip to Israel and the West Bank a few years ago. My heart breaks.

Of course, I don’t have any solutions or answers for us. But I do have my heart that has the capacity to hold the complexity of this harrowing moment.

In today’s writing on my publication ‘The Sacred Ebb’ on Substack, I share a poem I wrote last week, ‘Tending to the soul in times of terror.’

These are the opening stanzas. You can visit the link in my bio to read the full poem and a post with my humble, limited, & heart-centered reflections from my trip.

Tending to the soul in times of terror
By Shannon Algeo

I am sitting with my heart,
a heart that aches
for humanity

I am sitting with mind,
a mind that spins
with insanity

I notice my body,
a body that pulses
with adrenaline, cortisol, and chaos.

And I wonder,
“If I settle the wars within,
will I, then, be able to offer
this earth some modicum of peace?”

Can peace ripple
from one soul to another? F*ck yes.

My compulsive relationship to my smartphone has inspired me to research and explore new ways of caring for myself and my creative capacity.

Last year, when I was just at the beginning of my research for my Master’s thesis, which focuses on compulsive smartphone use, attachment theory, and poetry therapy (yes, poetry therapy!), I was cautiously considering the possibility of doing a “smartphone fast.” I was both fantasizing about and dreading the thought of a flip phone life.

At the time, I knew I had been spending way too much time on my device, and it felt compulsive. I wanted to make a change, but I did not know how.

So, on this day, I mustered up enough desire, will, and strength, and I left my smartphone at home so that I could be alone with myself—away from all the many digital distractions.

I walked twenty minutes to the café, ordered my drink at the counter, sat down, and opened my journal to a blank page. Then, without thinking at all, I hurriedly grabbed for my right pants pocket only to find it was flat and empty.

I sat with this compulsion, thirst, and need for the reliable drug that so consistently helped me to fill the void. I felt an empty sense of grief. In the absence of my pacifier, I instead took hold of my pen.

The words that came flowing out became a poem, “Reaching for the phone I left at home on purpose” which you can read (or listen to via audio recording) on my new Substack, ‘The Sacred Ebb.’

The shadow is any aspect of ourselves that was cast into exile. Oftentimes, as a result of this distancing from a part of ourselves, we (unconsciously) project the disowned self onto an other or others. Social media (and I would argue this includes dating apps) may accelerate, amplify, and exacerbate this process of projection—allowing us infinite and unboundaried opportunities to project the shadow self onto the illusion of other people’s digital personas.

I am so excited for this event tonight (12/8 at 7pm Mountain time) taught by Jungian Analyst and Somatic Psychotherapist Jane Clapp (@jungiansomatics) of the Calgary Jung Society (@calgaryjungsoc).

Join us on Friday, December 8th at 7pm Mountain Time for a Zoom lecture with Jane Clapp, @jungiansomatics on ‘Social Media and the Collective Unconscious: Archetypal Algorithms and the Colonization of the Psyche’

“Considering the colonization of the human psyche, which has been driven by greed and hunger for power during this period of end-stage capitalism and woven into algorithms that infect the unconscious, I argue that social media will impact the evolution of all cultures across the globe.
Certainly, an analysand’s social media use can impact their capacity to develop a symbolic life and the egoic strength necessary for individuation, yet many Jungians have underestimated the influence of this cultural phenomenon on both the individual and collective psyche. Jane believes Jungians have much to offer due to our understanding of the unconscious and the archetypal realm.
In this seminar, Jane brings the neurobiology of addiction together with the myth of Theseus and Ariadne to explore the handheld amorphous labyrinth of social media as it impacts both the individual and the cultural anima.”

When someone says ‘no’ to you,
you say ‘yes’ to yourself.

She said what she said 👏

Belonging is a core & fundamental human need. We need to belong, to be accepted, to be chosen, to be wanted, to be embraced, and to be loved.

And yet, sometimes in this wild human experience, we experience the exact opposite—the sting of rejection. A door slammed in the face. A feeling of being anything but chosen. Someone else’s compost, tossed back to the earth with the cow’s manure.

In these moments, the sovereignty of the Self must be reclaimed 👑 Dignity. Self-respect. And a nourishing nectar of self-love must be poured warm over the feelings of worthlessness, scum, and salt in the wound of being abandoned or unmet.

We are each royalty, stars in the center of our Universes, heroes on our own journey toward the shadows and the light.

By definition, the practice of saying YES to yourself is Selfish. And sometimes a Sweet Selfishness of the Soul is indeed required to mend the pieces of brokenness so that we can step fully into the whole of who we are.

Keep Rising, dear ones. We are living, breathing ancestors reclaiming our dignity and embodying our royalty in realtime. And we deserve to be chosen, again and again and again and again. 

The choice starts with me and with you.

“Stop projecting onto me!”

But what is projection, really? And what is its function in our psyche?

A disowned, or exiled, part of myself is a piece of me that has been castaway into the shadow of my psyche. I cannot see this part in my personality or in my known ego structure because it has been castaway into the Unconscious. “Byeee girlie” 👋

Because I cannot find or access the part within, I locate and see it in YOU. “Oh heyyy girl, you are now the object of my projections, how does it feel??!” 

This may be something in myself that I desire. Confidence. Ease. Grace. I may say to myself, “wow she probably has NO insecurities, she is always so confident.”

Or this may be a projection of an Archetypal figure like a Mother. Wise Spiritual Guru. Victim. Hero.

Or this could be strength. “You make the decisions, I don’t know what I’m doing- but you always seem to know.”

The slippery trickiness of projection is that it usually cannot be easily tracked because it is an Unconscious identification of the disowned Self in an Other. Notice the charge because usually there is one. Jealousy. Desire. Disgust. Anger.

Projection is not “bad.” It is a doorway, a threshold, for us to increase conscious awareness of the Unconscious and reclaim any Lost Ones within who may have been exiled along the way.
